06507nam a22011415i 9781400889747DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20182018nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008897477 a10.1515/97814008897472doi  a(DE-B1597)491101  a(OCoLC)1029759786  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBP63.P2bZ36 2019 7aREL0370102bisacsh04a297.0954912231 aZaman, Muhammad Qasim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIslam in Pakistan :bA History /cMuhammad Qasim Zaman. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (432 p.) :b6 tables. 3 maps.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in Muslim Politics ;v6800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Transliteration, Spelling, Abbreviations, and Other Conventions -- tMaps -- tIntroduction -- tChapter one. Islamic Identities in Colonial India -- tChapter two. Modernism and Its Ethical Commitments -- tChapter three. The `Ulama and the State -- tChapter four. Islamism and the Sovereignty of God -- tChapter five. Religious Minorities and the Anxieties of an Islamic Identity -- tChapter six. The Contested Terrain of Sufism -- tChapter seven. Religion, Violence, and the State -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tPrinceton studies in muslim politics -- tA note on the type0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first book to explore the modern history of Islam in South AsiaThe first modern state to be founded in the name of Islam, Pakistan was the largest Muslim country in the world at the time of its establishment in 1947. Today it is the second-most populous, after Indonesia. Islam in Pakistan is the first comprehensive book to explore Islam's evolution in this region over the past century and a half, from the British colonial era to the present day. Muhammad Qasim Zaman presents a rich historical account of this major Muslim nation, insights into the rise and gradual decline of Islamic modernist thought in the South Asian region, and an understanding of how Islam has fared in the contemporary world. Much attention has been given to Pakistan's role in sustaining the Afghan struggle against the Soviet occupation in the 1980s, in the growth of the Taliban in the 1990s, and in the War on Terror after 9/11. But as Zaman shows, the nation's significance in matters relating to Islam has much deeper roots. Since the late nineteenth century, South Asia has witnessed important initiatives toward rethinking core Islamic texts and traditions in the interest of their compatibility with the imperatives of modern life. Traditionalist scholars and their institutions, too, have had a prominent presence in the region, as have Islamism and Sufism. Pakistan did not merely inherit these and other aspects of Islam. Rather, it has been and remains a site of intense contestation over Islam's public place, meaning, and interpretation. Examining how facets of Islam have been pivotal in Pakistani history, Islam in Pakistan offers sweeping perspectives on what constitutes an Islamic state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aIslam and statezPakistanzPāṭa. 0aIslamzPakistanzPāṭaxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Islam / History.2bisacsh  aAfghan struggle.  aAhmadis.  aBritish India.  aBritish colonial rule.  aDeobandis.  aGod.  aIslam.  aIslamic law.  aIslamic state.  aIslamic texts.  aIslamism.  aIslamists.  aMawdudi.  aMuslim identity.  aMuslim minorities.  aMuslim.  aPakistan.  aShi`a.  aSouth Asia.  aSufism.  aSunni.  aTaliban.  aWar on Terror.  a`ulama.  aauthoritarianism.  acolonial India.  acolonial Pakistan.  amode